In[22]:
# read in the metadata
metadata <- fread('counts/metadata.tsv.gz', sep='\t')

Here, I'm choosing to focus on cytotoxic T cells and macrophages as they were the focus on the article. The authors show that T cells gain an exhausted phenotype after chemotherapy and relocate spatially. Hopefully pseudotime of the treatment stages will help to identify markers associated with change.

In[23]:
# read in the counts and create Seurat object
object <- CreateSeuratObject(Read10X(data.dir='counts', gene.column=1), meta.data=metadata)
object <- object %>% subset(cells=metadata[cell_type %chin% c('Tem/Trm cytotoxic T cells', 'Macrophages'), cell_name])

Typically, I would identify doublets and filter but will leave that out for now. Common metrics are percent mito and percent ribo. This represents the fraction of a cells measured transcriptome that mapped to mitochondrial or ribosomal rna. You can also look at hemoglobin percentages in case cells were contaminated during biopsy, but will also leave that out for now.

In[24]:
object[['percent.mt']] <- PercentageFeatureSet(object, pattern='^MT-')
object[['percent.rb']] <- PercentageFeatureSet(object, pattern='^RP[LS]')

I can visualize the distributions of the main metrics and split by treatment_stage to get a quick visual of the data. There are other forms of visualization like scatter plots and metrics like reads mapped per cell. For now, filtering on these metrics should be okay. Visualizing in log scale helps to show lower tails.

Overall, the data are relatively cleaner than expected. I expected cells with higher MT percentages. The RB percentages don't show anything concerning but are higher than expected. The 10X chemistry is older as well which means number of genes detected might be lower. Based on these violin plots, we can choose appropriate cutoffs.

After preprocessing, I normalize the data per cell and log transform. The default for variable gene selection is 2000 but I am increasing to 3000 because we have more genes in the reference. The dataset is diseased and contains case/control so modeling more genes downstream may be helpful.

In[63]:

Calculate 95% cumulative variance for pca dimensions. I could correlate dimensions with covariates to see if certain ones need to be removed but choosing to leave that out here. The data are clean and filtered, batch correction is performed and so removing dimensions completely should be unnecessary for now.

In[12]:
pca_stdev <- object[['pca']]@stdev

pca_var <- pca_stdev^2
pca_var_exp <- pca_var / sum(pca_var)

cum_var <- cumsum(pca_var_exp)
num_dims <- which(cum_var >= 0.95)[1]

Performing UMAP reduction to generate embeddings for visualization. I'm doing this on the PCA dimensions which are not batch corrected.

In[13]:
object <- object %>% RunUMAP(dims=seq(num_dims), reduction='pca')

Interesting to note here, in terms of cell type specific grouping, there is minimal batch effect. The cells are grouping as either macrophages or t cells with their respective populations. However, the within cell type batch effect is more prominent, especially in the macrophage population. Due to the stronger batch effect, the macrophage population is not as densly grouped.

I am choosing to perform batch correction with Harmony as it performs well in benchmarking, is easy to use, and offers flexibility to the strength of correction.
